ebsite }}</ref> of 2000, there were 140 people, 79 households, and 27 families residing in the CDP. The [[population density]] was 14.0 people per square mile (5.4/km\u00b2). There were 247 housing units at an average density of 24.7 per square mile (9.5/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the CDP was 97.86% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.71% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.71% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], and 0.71% from two or more races.\n\nThere were 79 households out of which 11.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 29.1% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 5.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 65.8% were non-families. 40.5% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 1.77 and the average family size was 2.44.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 8.6% under the age of 18, 4.3% from 18 to 24, 42.1% from 25 to 44, 35.0% from 45 to 64, and 10.0% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females, there were 122.2 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 113.3 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $25,000, and the median income for a family was $50,625. Males had a median income of $38,125 versus $17,813 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $31,618. There were 7.4% of families and 15.8% of the population living below the [[poverty line]], including 18.2% of under eighteens and 10.5% of those over 64.\n\n{{gallery\n|title=Images of Cooke City-Silver Gate, Montana\n|footer=\n|lines=3\n|width=150\n|File:2003-08-17 Miners Saloon in Cooke City, Montana.jpg|Miners Saloon, 2003\n|File:CookeCityMTJanuary2010.jpg|Looking East, January 2010\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Wikivoyage|Cooke City}}\n{{commons category|Cooke City, Montana}}\n{{Park County, Montana}}\n{{Tower Roosevelt}}\n{{Montana}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Park County, Montana]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Montana]]\n", "name_user": "Old Hoar's Frost", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClimate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cooke_City-Silver_Gate,_Montana"}
{"title_page": "Academy of the Hebrew Language", "text_new": "{{lead too short|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Academy of the Hebrew Language\n| native_name         = {{Hebrew|\u05d4\u05d0\u05e7\u05d3\u05de\u05d9\u05d4 \u05dc\u05dc\u05e9\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea}}\n|native_name_lang=he\n| former_name         = Hebrew Language Committee\n| image               = File:Academy of the Hebrew Language.png\n| image_border        = \n| size                = 250px\n| alt                 = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption             = \n| abbreviation        = \n| motto               = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = 1890 \u2013 Hebrew Language Committee<br />1953 \u2013 Academy of the Hebrew Language\n| founder             = [[Eliezer Ben Yehuda]]\n| type                = [[Governmental organization|GO]]\n| status              = [[Language regulator]]\n| purpose             = To regulate the Hebrew language\n| professional_title  = <!-- for professional associations -->\n| headquarters        = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Givat Ram]], [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]]\n}}\n| coords              = {{coord|31|46|20.34|N|35|11|54.71|E|display=inline,title|type:landmark}}\n| region_served       = Hebrew-speaking population\n| services            = \n| membership          = \n| language            = [[Modern Hebrew]]\n| leader_title        = President\n| leader_name         = [[Moshe Bar-Asher]]\n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n| affiliations        = \n| budget              = \n| num_staff           = 38\n| num_volunteers      = \n| slogan              = \n| website             = {{URL|http://hebrew-academy.org.il/}}\n| remarks             = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Academy of the Hebrew Language''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d4\u05b8\u05d0\u05b8\u05e7\u05b8\u05d3\u05b6\u05de\u05b0\u05d9\u05b8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05b7\u05dc\u05b8\u05bc\u05e9\u05c1\u05d5\u05b9\u05df \u05d4\u05b8\u05e2\u05b4\u05d1\u05b0\u05e8\u05b4\u05d9\u05ea}}, ''ha-akademya la-lashon ha-ivrit'') was established by the [[Israel]]i government in 1953 as the \"supreme institution for scholarship on the Hebrew language in the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]] of [[Givat Ram]] campus.\"<ref>[http://www.lprc.org.il/LPRC/images/PDF/phd_yitzhaki.pdf Minority Languages and Language Policy: The Case of Arabic in Israel] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426061017/http://www.lprc.org.il/LPRC/images/PDF/phd_yitzhaki.pdf |date=April 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Academy of the Hebrew Language.JPG|right|thumb|350px|The Academy of the Hebrew Language building at the [[Hebrew University]] Givat Ram campus]]\nThe Academy replaced the Hebrew Language Committee (Va\u02bbad ha-lashon ha-\u02bbIvrit) established in 1890 by [[Eliezer Ben-Yehuda]], who was its first president. As Hebrew became the spoken language in Palestine and was adopted by the [[Education in Israel|educational system]], the Hebrew Language Committee published bulletins and dictionaries. It coined thousands of words that are in everyday use today.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hZqpCrG3qw0C&pg=PA504 ''The New Jewish Encyclopedia'', ed. David Bridger]</ref>\n\nIts successor, the Academy of the Hebrew Language, has continued this mission of creating new [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] words to keep up modern usage.\n\nAlthough the academy's business is creating new words from Hebrew roots and structures to replace loanwords derived from other languages, its own name is a loanword, \"akademya.\"<ref name=\"Hebrew Academy\">[http://en.hebrew-academy.org.il/ Hebrew Academy]</ref> It addresses this irony on its English website.<ref>[http://en.hebrew-academy.org.il/birth-of-a-word/when-should-foreign-words-be-replaced-by-hebrew-words/ When Should Foreign Words Be Replaced By Hebrew Words?]</ref>\n\nThe Academy's mission, as defined in its constitution, is \"to direct the development of Hebrew in light of its nature\" (\u05dc\u05db\u05d5\u05d5\u05df \u05d0\u05ea \u05d3\u05e8\u05db\u05d9 \u05d4\u05ea\u05e4\u05ea\u05d7\u05d5\u05ea\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05dc\u05e9\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05dc\u05e4\u05d9 \u05d8\u05d1\u05e2\u05d4).<ref>[[Ghil'ad Zuckermann]] argues that this is an \"oxymoronic\" mission impossible: \"If the '''nature''' of a language is to evolve in a specific direction, why '''direct''' it by language policing?\", see Zuckermann, Ghil'ad (2008), [http://www.zuckermann.org/pdf/Realistic_Prescriptivism_Academy.pdf Realistic Prescriptivism: The Academy of the Hebrew Language, its Campaign of \"Good Grammar\" and Lexpionage, and the Native Israeli Speakers]. ''Israel Studies in Language and Society'' 1, pp. 135\u2013154.</ref> The Academy sets standards for modern Hebrew grammar, orthography, transliteration, and punctuation based on the historical development of the language. It also writes a Hebrew Historical Dictionary.<ref>According to Zuckermann, \"the Historical Dictionary Project is the Academy's most important contribution\", see Zuckermann, Ghil'ad (2008), [http://www.zuckermann.org/pdf/Realistic_Prescriptivism_Academy.pdf Realistic Prescriptivism: The Academy of the Hebrew Language, its Campaign of \"Good Grammar\" and Lexpionage, and the Native Israeli Speakers]. ''Israel Studies in Language and Society'' 1, pp. 135\u2013154.</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe plenum consists of 23 members. In addition, the academy employs 15 academic advisors, among them respected scholars of language, linguistics, Judaic studies, and Bible. The Academy's decisions are binding on all governmental agencies, including the [[Israel Broadcasting Authority]].<ref name=\"Hebrew Academy\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Study of the Hebrew language]]\n* [[List of language regulators]]\n* [[Revival of the Hebrew language]]\n* [[Historical Dictionary Project of the Hebrew Language]]\n* [[Autoridad Nasionala del Ladino]], a language regulator for Ladino\n* [[YIVO|YIVO (Yidisher Visnshaftlekher Institut)]], a language regulator for Yiddish\n* [[Academy of the Arabic Language in Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://en.hebrew-academy.org.il/ Academy of the Hebrew Language] \u2013 official website (English)\n* [https://overseas.huji.ac.il/academics/hebrew-and-other-languages/study-hebrew-language-at-the-hebrew-university-of-jerusalem/ Rothberg International School The Hebrew University of Jerusalem]\n\n{{Hebrew language}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Academy Of The Hebrew Language, The}}\n[[Category:Civic and political organizations of Israel]]\n[[Category:Hebrew language]]\n[[Category:Language regulators]]\n[[Category:1953 establishments in Israel]]\n", "text_old": "{{lead too short|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Academy of the Hebrew Language\n| native_name         = {{Hebrew|\u05d4\u05d0\u05e7\u05d3\u05de\u05d9\u05d4 \u05dc\u05dc\u05e9\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea}}\n|native_name_lang=he\n| former_name         = Hebrew Language Committee\n| image               = File:Academy of the Hebrew Language.png\n| image_border        = \n| size                = 250px\n| alt                 = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption             = \n| abbreviation        = \n| motto               = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = 1890 - Hebrew Language Committee<br />1953 - Academy of the Hebrew Language\n| founder             = [[Eliezer Ben Yehuda]]\n| type                = [[Governmental organization|GO]]\n| status              = [[Language regulator]]\n| purpose             = To regulate the Hebrew language\n| professional_title  = <!-- for professional associations -->\n| headquarters        = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Givat Ram]], [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]]\n}}\n| coords              = {{coord|31|46|20.34|N|35|11|54.71|E|display=inline,title|type:landmark}}\n| region_served       = Hebrew-speaking population\n| services            = \n| membership          = \n| language            = [[Modern Hebrew]]\n| leader_title        = President\n| leader_name         = [[Moshe Bar-Asher]]\n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n| affiliations        = \n| budget              = \n| num_staff           = 38\n| num_volunteers      = \n| slogan              = \n| website             = {{URL|http://hebrew-academy.org.il/}}\n| remarks             = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Academy of the Hebrew Language''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d4\u05b8\u05d0\u05b8\u05e7\u05b8\u05d3\u05b6\u05de\u05b0\u05d9\u05b8\u05d4 \u05dc\u05b7\u05dc\u05b8\u05bc\u05e9\u05c1\u05d5\u05b9\u05df \u05d4\u05b8\u05e2\u05b4\u05d1\u05b0\u05e8\u05b4\u05d9\u05ea}}, ''ha-akademya la-lashon ha-ivrit'') was established by the [[Israel]]i government in 1953 as the \"supreme institution for scholarship on the Hebrew language in the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]] of [[Givat Ram]] campus.\"<ref>[http://www.lprc.org.il/LPRC/images/PDF/phd_yitzhaki.pdf Minority Languages and Language Policy: The Case of Arabic in Israel] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426061017/http://www.lprc.org.il/LPRC/images/PDF/phd_yitzhaki.pdf |date=April 26, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Academy of the Hebrew Language.JPG|right|thumb|350px|The Academy of the Hebrew Language building at the [[Hebrew University]] - Givat Ram campus]]\nThe Academy replaced the Hebrew Language Committee (Va\u02bbad ha-lashon ha-\u02bbIvrit) established in 1890 by [[Eliezer Ben-Yehuda]], who was its first president. As Hebrew became the spoken language in Palestine and was adopted by the [[Education in Israel|educational system]], the Hebrew Language Committee published bulletins and dictionaries. It coined thousands of words that are in everyday use today.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hZqpCrG3qw0C&pg=PA504 The New Jewish Encyclopedia, ed. David Bridger]</ref>\n\nIts successor, the Academy of the Hebrew Language, has continued this mission of creating new [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] words to keep up modern usage.\n\nAlthough the academy's business is creating new words from Hebrew roots and structures to replace loanwords derived from other languages, its own name is a loanword, \"akademya.\"<ref name=\"Hebrew Academy\">[http://en.hebrew-academy.org.il/ Hebrew Academy]</ref> It addresses this irony on its English website.<ref>[http://en.hebrew-academy.org.il/birth-of-a-word/when-should-foreign-words-be-replaced-by-hebrew-words/ When Should Foreign Words Be Replaced By Hebrew Words?]</ref>\n\nThe Academy's mission, as defined in its constitution, is \"to direct the development of Hebrew in light of its nature\" (\u05dc\u05db\u05d5\u05d5\u05df \u05d0\u05ea \u05d3\u05e8\u05db\u05d9 \u05d4\u05ea\u05e4\u05ea\u05d7\u05d5\u05ea\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05dc\u05e9\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05dc\u05e4\u05d9 \u05d8\u05d1\u05e2\u05d4).<ref>[[Ghil'ad Zuckermann]] argues that this is an \"oxymoronic\" mission impossible: \"If the '''nature''' of a language is to evolve in a specific direction, why '''direct''' it by language policing?\", see Zuckermann, Ghil'ad (2008), [http://www.zuckermann.org/pdf/Realistic_Prescriptivism_Academy.pdf Realistic Prescriptivism: The Academy of the Hebrew Language, its Campaign of \"Good Grammar\" and Lexpionage, and the Native Israeli Speakers]. ''Israel Studies in Language and Society'' 1, pp. 135\u2013154.</ref> The Academy sets standards for modern Hebrew grammar, orthography, transliteration, and punctuation based on the historical development of the language. It also writes a Hebrew Historical Dictionary.<ref>According to Zuckermann, \"the Historical Dictionary Project is the Academy's most important contribution\", see Zuckermann, Ghil'ad (2008), [http://www.zuckermann.org/pdf/Realistic_Prescriptivism_Academy.pdf Realistic Prescriptivism: The Academy of the Hebrew Language, its Campaign of \"Good Grammar\" and Lexpionage, and the Native Israeli Speakers]. ''Israel Studies in Language and Society'' 1, pp. 135\u2013154.</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe plenum consists of 23 members. In addition, the academy employs 15 academic advisors, among them respected scholars of language, linguistics, Judaic studies, and Bible. The Academy's decisions are binding on all governmental agencies, including the [[Israel Broadcasting Authority]].<ref name=\"Hebrew Academy\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Study of the Hebrew language]]\n* [[List of language regulators]]\n* [[Revival of the Hebrew language]]\n* [[Historical Dictionary Project of the Hebrew Language]]\n* [[Autoridad Nasionala del Ladino]], a language regulator for Ladino\n* [[YIVO|YIVO (Yidisher Visnshaftlekher Institut)]], a language regulator for Yiddish\n* [[Academy of the Arabic Language in Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://en.hebrew-academy.org.il/ Academy of the Hebrew Language] - Official Website (English)\n*[https://overseas.huji.ac.il/academics/hebrew-and-other-languages/study-hebrew-language-at-the-hebrew-university-of-jerusalem/ Rothberg International School The Hebrew University of Jerusalem]\n\n{{Hebrew language}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Academy Of The Hebrew Language, The}}\n[[Category:Civic and political organizations of Israel]]\n[[Category:Hebrew language]]\n[[Category:Language regulators]]\n[[Category:1953 establishments in Israel]]\n", "name_user": "Jprg1966", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_of_the_Hebrew_Language"}
{"title_page": "Anne Claire Poirier", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian film producer}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Anne Claire Poirier.jpg\n| name         = Anne Claire Poirier\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of Canada|OC]]\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1932|6|6}}\n| birth_place  = Saint-Hyacinthe, Quebec, Canada\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation   = Film producer<br>Film director<br>Screenwriter\n| yearsactive  = 1963-1996\n}}\n\n'''Anne Claire Poirier''' [[Order of Canada|O.C.]] (born 6 June 1932) is a Canadian film producer, director and screenwriter. She was the only female filmmaker on the National Film Board of Canada in the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Gendering the Nation: Canadia Women's Cinema |author1=Kay Armatage |author2=Kass Banning |author3=Brenda Longfellow |authorlink3=Brenda Longfellow |author4=Janine Marchessault |authorlink4=Janine Marchessault |publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1999|isbn=|location=|pages=8}}</ref> Her first film, the black and white surrealist fictional documentary ''De m\u00e8re en fille'' (1968), critiques social codes of motherhood and investigates the psychological experience of pregnancy. The film had a significant influence on the nascenct feminist movement in Canada. ''De m\u00e8re en fille'' is the first feature film ever directed by a French-Canadian woman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/bios/anne-claire-poirier |title=Canadian Film Encyclopedia - Anne Claire Poirier |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726115631/http://www.tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/bios/anne-claire-poirier |archivedate=26 July 2011 }}</ref> Poirier's film ''[[A Scream from Silence|Mourir \u00e0 tue-t\u00eate]]'' competed in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[1979 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/1936/year/1979.html |title=Festival de Cannes: A Scream from Silence |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120730032328/http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/1936/year/1979.html |archivedate=30 July 2012  }}</ref> ''Mourir \u00e0 tue-t\u00eate,'' which aboards the subject of rape, remains Poirier's best known film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/bios/anne-claire-poirier |title=Canadian Film Encyclopedia - Anne Claire Poirier |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726115631/http://www.tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/bios/anne-claire-poirier |archivedate=26 July 2011 }}</ref> Her 1974 film ''Les Filles du Roi'' explores a history of masculinity in Quebec.<ref>{{Citation|last=Canada|first=National Film Board of|title=They Called Us 'Les Filles du Roy'|url=https://www.nfb.ca/film/they_called_us_filles_du_roy/|language=en|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nPoirier was born in [[Saint-Hyacinthe, Quebec]].  In 1988 she was awarded the [[Prix Albert-Tessier]]. In 1996, she directed the feature-length documentary ''[[Tu as cri\u00e9: Let me go]]'' to understand the events that led to the murder of her daughter. ''Tu as cri\u00e9: Let me go'' received numerous awards including the [[Genie Award]] for Best Feature Length Documentary.<ref>{{cite web|title=IMDb - Genie Awards (1997)|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000276/1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Poirier received a [[Governor General's Performing Arts Award]] for Lifetime Artistic Achievement in film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anne Claire Poirier biography- GGPAA|url=http://ggpaa.ca/award-recipients/2001/poirier-anne-claire.aspx}}</ref>\nShe was appointed an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |title=Order of Canada: Anne Claire Poirier |website=The [[Governor General of Canada]] |url=http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=8537&t=12 |access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Fiction===\n*''La fin des \u00e9t\u00e9s'' (Short film, 1964)\n*''Le savoir-faire s'impose'' (Short film, 1971)\n*''Le temps de l'avant'' (1975)\n*''[[A Scream from Silence]] (Mourir \u00e0 tue-t\u00eate)'' (1979)\n*''[[Beyond Forty]] (La Quarantaine)'' (1982)\n*''[[Salut Victor]]'' (1988)\n\n===Documentaries===\n*''Stampede'' (Short, 1962)\n*''Nomade de l'Ouest'' (Short, 1962)\n*''30 Minutes, Mr. Plummer'' (Short, 1963)\n*''Les ludions'' (Short, 1965)\n*''De m\u00e8re en fille'' (1968)\n*''Les filles du Roy'' (1974)\n*''Il y a longtemps que je t'aime'' (1989)\n*''[[Tu as cri\u00e9: Let me go]]'' (1996)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of female film and television directors]]\n* [[List of LGBT-related films directed by women]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0688503|Anne Claire Poirier}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poirier, Anne Claire}}\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian film producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian women film directors]]\n[[Category:Canadian screenwriters in French]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Quebec]]\n[[Category:Canadian documentary film directors]]\n[[Category:Directors of Genie and Canadian Screen Award winners for Best Documentary Film]]\n[[Category:Governor General's Performing Arts Award winners]]\n[[Category:Canadian women film producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Women documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Prix Albert-Tessier winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian film producer}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        =\n| name         = Anne Claire Poirier\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of Canada|OC]]\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1932|6|6}}\n| birth_place  = Saint-Hyacinthe, Quebec, Canada\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation   = Film producer<br>Film director<br>Screenwriter\n| yearsactive  = 1963-1996\n}}\n\n'''Anne Claire Poirier''' [[Order of Canada|O.C.]] (born 6 June 1932) is a Canadian film producer, director and screenwriter. She was the only female filmmaker on the National Film Board of Canada in the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Gendering the Nation: Canadia Women's Cinema |author1=Kay Armatage |author2=Kass Banning |author3=Brenda Longfellow |authorlink3=Brenda Longfellow |author4=Janine Marchessault |authorlink4=Janine Marchessault |publisher=University of Toronto Press|year=1999|isbn=|location=|pages=8}}</ref> Her first film, the black and white surrealist fictional documentary ''De m\u00e8re en fille'' (1968), critiques social codes of motherhood and investigates the psychological experience of pregnancy. The film had a significant influence on the nascenct feminist movement in Canada. ''De m\u00e8re en fille'' is the first feature film ever directed by a French-Canadian woman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/bios/anne-claire-poirier |title=Canadian Film Encyclopedia - Anne Claire Poirier |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726115631/http://www.tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/bios/anne-claire-poirier |archivedate=26 July 2011 }}</ref> Poirier's film ''[[A Scream from Silence|Mourir \u00e0 tue-t\u00eate]]'' competed in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[1979 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/1936/year/1979.html |title=Festival de Cannes: A Scream from Silence |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120730032328/http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/1936/year/1979.html |archivedate=30 July 2012  }}</ref> ''Mourir \u00e0 tue-t\u00eate,'' which aboards the subject of rape, remains Poirier's best known film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/bios/anne-claire-poirier |title=Canadian Film Encyclopedia - Anne Claire Poirier |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726115631/http://www.tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/bios/anne-claire-poirier |archivedate=26 July 2011 }}</ref> Her 1974 film ''Les Filles du Roi'' explores a history of masculinity in Quebec.<ref>{{Citation|last=Canada|first=National Film Board of|title=They Called Us 'Les Filles du Roy'|url=https://www.nfb.ca/film/they_called_us_filles_du_roy/|language=en|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nPoirier was born in [[Saint-Hyacinthe, Quebec]].  In 1988 she was awarded the [[Prix Albert-Tessier]]. In 1996, she directed the feature-length documentary ''[[Tu as cri\u00e9: Let me go]]'' to understand the events that led to the murder of her daughter. ''Tu as cri\u00e9: Let me go'' received numerous awards including the [[Genie Award]] for Best Feature Length Documentary.<ref>{{cite web|title=IMDb - Genie Awards (1997)|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000276/1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Poirier received a [[Governor General's Performing Arts Award]] for Lifetime Artistic Achievement in film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anne Claire Poirier biography- GGPAA|url=http://ggpaa.ca/award-recipients/2001/poirier-anne-claire.aspx}}</ref>\nShe was appointed an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |title=Order of Canada: Anne Claire Poirier |website=The [[Governor General of Canada]] |url=http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=8537&t=12 |access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Fiction===\n*''La fin des \u00e9t\u00e9s'' (Short film, 1964)\n*''Le savoir-faire s'impose'' (Short film, 1971)\n*''Le temps de l'avant'' (1975)\n*''[[A Scream from Silence]] (Mourir \u00e0 tue-t\u00eate)'' (1979)\n*''[[Beyond Forty]] (La Quarantaine)'' (1982)\n*''[[Salut Victor]]'' (1988)\n\n===Documentaries===\n*''Stampede'' (Short, 1962)\n*''Nomade de l'Ouest'' (Short, 1962)\n*''30 Minutes, Mr. Plummer'' (Short, 1963)\n*''Les ludions'' (Short, 1965)\n*''De m\u00e8re en fille'' (1968)\n*''Les filles du Roy'' (1974)\n*''Il y a longtemps que je t'aime'' (1989)\n*''[[Tu as cri\u00e9: Let me go]]'' (1996)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of female film and television directors]]\n* [[List of LGBT-related films directed by women]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0688503|Anne Claire Poirier}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poirier, Anne Claire}}\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian film producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian women film directors]]\n[[Category:Canadian screenwriters in French]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Quebec]]\n[[Category:Canadian documentary film directors]]\n[[Category:Directors of Genie and Canadian Screen Award winners for Best Documentary Film]]\n[[Category:Governor General's Performing Arts Award winners]]\n[[Category:Canadian women film producers]]\n[[Category:Canadian women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Women documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Prix Albert-Tessier winners]]\n", "name_user": "Dsp13", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:+image", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anne_Claire_Poirier"}
{"title_page": "Meat Wave", "text_new": "{{Notability|Music|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Meat Wave\n| image               = \n| caption             =\n| image_size          =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               =\n| origin              = USA\n| genre               = [[punk rock]]<ref>https://www.punknews.org/review/13889/meat-wave-delusion-moon</ref>\n| years_active        = 2011&ndash;present\n| label               = SideOneDummy Records\n| associated_acts     = Elephant Gun, Truman & His Trophy, Pink Torpedo\n| website             = [http://www.meatwaveband.com meatwaveband.com]\n| current_members     = Chris Sutter<br/>Joe Gac<br/>Ryan Wizniak\n| past_members        =\n}}\n\n'''Meat Wave''' is a [[Musical ensemble|punk band]] from Chicago, USA. Their music is described as post-something<ref>https://www.ohmyrockness.com/bands/meat-wave#!</ref>, melancholic<ref>https://www.punknews.org/review/14905/meat-wave-the-incessant</ref> and aggressive<ref name='allmusic'>https://www.allmusic.com/artist/meat-wave-mn0003291057/biography</ref>.\n \n==History==\nMeat Wave was formed in 2011 after Truman & His Trophy disbanded. The trio set out to play with a more aggressive tone than they were used to in their previous ensembles.<ref  name='allmusic'>https://www.allmusic.com/artist/meat-wave-mn0003291057/biography</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n* Chris Sutter \u2013 lead vocals, guitars\n* Joe Gac \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n* Ryan Wizniak \u2013 drums\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* 2017 '''''The Incessant'''''\n* 2015 '''''Delusion Moon'''''\n* 2015 '''''Brother (EP)'''''\n* 2012 '''''Meat Wave'''''\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.meatwaveband.com/ Official Website]\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|Music|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Meat Wave\n| image               = \n| caption             =\n| image_size          =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               =\n| origin              =\n| genre               = [[punk rock]]<ref>https://www.punknews.org/review/13889/meat-wave-delusion-moon</ref>\n| years_active        = 2012&ndash;present\n| label               = SideOneDummy Records\n| associated_acts     =\n| website             = [http://www.meatwaveband.com meatwaveband.com]\n| current_members     = Chris Sutter<br/>Joe Gac<br/>Ryan Wizniak\n| past_members        =\n}}\n\n'''Meat Wave''' is a [[Musical ensemble|punk band]] from USA. Their music is described as post-something<ref>https://www.ohmyrockness.com/bands/meat-wave#!</ref>, melancholic<ref>https://www.punknews.org/review/14905/meat-wave-the-incessant</ref> and aggressive<ref name='allmusic'>https://www.allmusic.com/artist/meat-wave-mn0003291057/biography</ref>.\n \n==History==\nMeat Wave was formed in 2011 after Truman & His Trophy disbanded. The trio set out to play with a more aggressive tone than they were used to in their previous ensembles.<ref  name='allmusic'>https://www.allmusic.com/artist/meat-wave-mn0003291057/biography</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n* Chris Sutter \u2013 lead vocals, guitars\n* Joe Gac \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n* Ryan Wizniak \u2013 drums\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* 2017 '''''The Incessant'''''\n* 2015 '''''Delusion Moon'''''\n* 2015 '''''Brother (EP)'''''\n* 2012 '''''Meat Wave'''''\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.meatwaveband.com/ Official Website]\n", "name_user": "Juhohame", "label": "safe", "comment": "USA, year they started, associated acts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meat_Wave"}
